003/**
004 * K.jpg's OpenSimplex 2, smooth variant ("SuperSimplex")
005 * <br>
006 * Using OpenSimplex 2 in its July 5, 2020 revision. This is the latest
007 * revision as of February 26, 2021.
008 * <ul>
009 *   <li>2D is standard simplex, modified to support larger kernels.
010 *   Implemented using a lookup table.</li>
011 *   <li>3D is "Re-oriented 8-point BCC noise" which constructs a
012 *   congruent BCC lattice in a much different way than usual.</li>
013 *   <li>4D uses a na√Øve pregenerated lookup table, and averages out
014 *   to the expected performance.</li>
015 * </ul>
016 * <br>
017 * This implements SquidLib's Noise2, Noise3, and Noise4 interfaces, allowing
018 * it to be used with the inner classes from {@link Noise} for things like layering
019 * octaves of noise with {@link Noise.Layered2D} or making ridged noise with
020 * {@link Noise.Ridged3D}. The {@link #getNoiseWithSeed(double, double, long)}
021 * methods just use the seed to offset the coordinates, splitting up the seed into
022 * 2, 3, or 4 smaller parts for 2D, 3D, and 4D respectively. This means the
023 * getNoiseWithSeed() methods need very large and different seeds for a visual
024 * difference to be apparent; just adding 1 to the seed won't help. The initial seed
025 * passed to {@link #OpenSimplex2S(long)} matters a lot; it can't be changed later.
026 * This is the smoother variant of OpenSimplex 2, and is expected to be slower than
027 * {@link OpenSimplex2F} or the Simplex noise in {@link FastNoise}.
028 */
029public class OpenSimplex2S implements Noise.Noise2D, Noise.Noise3D, Noise.Noise4D {
030        
031        private static final int PSIZE = 2048;
032        private static final int PMASK = 2047;
033
034        private short[] perm;
035        private Grad2[] permGrad2;
036        private Grad3[] permGrad3;
037        private Grad4[] permGrad4;
038
039        public OpenSimplex2S(){
040                this(1234567890987654321L);
041        }
042
043        public OpenSimplex2S(long seed) {
044                perm = new short[PSIZE];
045                permGrad2 = new Grad2[PSIZE];
046                permGrad3 = new Grad3[PSIZE];
047                permGrad4 = new Grad4[PSIZE];
048                short[] source = new short[PSIZE]; 
049                for (short i = 0; i < PSIZE; i++)
050                        source[i] = i;
051                for (int i = PSIZE - 1; i >= 0; i--) {
052                        seed = seed * 6364136223846793005L + 1442695040888963407L;
053                        int r = (int)((seed >>> 32) * (i + 1) >>> 32);
054                        perm[i] = source[r];
055                        permGrad2[i] = GRADIENTS_2D[perm[i]];
056                        permGrad3[i] = GRADIENTS_3D[perm[i]];
057                        permGrad4[i] = GRADIENTS_4D[perm[i]];
058                        source[r] = source[i];
059                }
060        }

066        /**
067         * 2D SuperSimplex noise, standard lattice orientation.
068         */
069        public double noise2(double x, double y) {
070                
071                // Get points for A2* lattice
072                double s = 0.366025403784439 * (x + y);
073                double xs = x + s, ys = y + s;
074                
075                return noise2_Base(xs, ys);
076        }

078        /**
079         * 2D SuperSimplex noise, with Y pointing down the main diagonal.
080         * Might be better for a 2D sandbox style game, where Y is vertical.
081         * Probably slightly less optimal for heightmaps or continent maps.
082         */
083        public double noise2_XBeforeY(double x, double y) {
084                
085                // Skew transform and rotation baked into one.
086                double xx = x * 0.7071067811865476;
087                double yy = y * 1.224744871380249;
088                
089                return noise2_Base(yy + xx, yy - xx);
090        }

092        /**
093         * 2D SuperSimplex noise base.
094         * Lookup table implementation inspired by DigitalShadow.
095         */
096        private double noise2_Base(double xs, double ys) {
097                double value = 0;
098                
099                // Get base points and offsets
100                long xsb = Noise.longFloor(xs), ysb = Noise.longFloor(ys);
101                double xsi = xs - xsb, ysi = ys - ysb;
102                
103                // Index to point list
104                int a = (int)(xsi + ysi);
105                int index =
106                        (a << 2) |
107                        (int)(xsi - ysi / 2 + 1 - a / 2.0) << 3 |
108                        (int)(ysi - xsi / 2 + 1 - a / 2.0) << 4;
109                
110                double ssi = (xsi + ysi) * -0.211324865405187;
111                double xi = xsi + ssi, yi = ysi + ssi;
112
113                // Point contributions
114                for (int i = 0; i < 4; i++) {
115                        LatticePoint2D c = LOOKUP_2D[index + i];
116
117                        double dx = xi + c.dx, dy = yi + c.dy;
118                        double attn = 2.0 / 3.0 - dx * dx - dy * dy;
119                        if (attn <= 0) continue;
120
121                        int pxm = ((int) xsb + c.xsv) & PMASK, pym = ((int) ysb + c.ysv) & PMASK;
122                        Grad2 grad = permGrad2[perm[pxm] ^ pym];
123                        double extrapolation = grad.dx * dx + grad.dy * dy;
124                        
125                        attn *= attn;
126                        value += attn * attn * extrapolation;
127                }
128                
129                return value;
130        }

132        /**
133         * 3D Re-oriented 8-point BCC noise, classic orientation
134         * Proper substitute for what 3D SuperSimplex would be,
135         * in light of Forbidden Formulae.
136         * Use noise3_XYBeforeZ or noise3_XZBeforeY instead, wherever appropriate.
137         */
138        public double noise3_Classic(double x, double y, double z) {
139                
140                // Re-orient the cubic lattices via rotation, to produce the expected look on cardinal planar slices.
141                // If texturing objects that don't tend to have cardinal plane faces, you could even remove this.
142                // Orthonormal rotation. Not a skew transform.
143                double r = (2.0 / 3.0) * (x + y + z);
144                double xr = r - x, yr = r - y, zr = r - z;
145                
146                // Evaluate both lattices to form a BCC lattice.
147                return noise3_BCC(xr, yr, zr);
148        }
149        
150        /**
151         * 3D Re-oriented 8-point BCC noise, with better visual isotropy in (X, Y).
152         * Recommended for 3D terrain and time-varied animations.
153         * The Z coordinate should always be the "different" coordinate in your use case.
154         * If Y is vertical in world coordinates, call noise3_XYBeforeZ(x, z, Y) or use noise3_XZBeforeY.
155         * If Z is vertical in world coordinates, call noise3_XYBeforeZ(x, y, Z).
156         * For a time varied animation, call noise3_XYBeforeZ(x, y, T).
157         */
158        public double noise3_XYBeforeZ(double x, double y, double z) {
159                
160                // Re-orient the cubic lattices without skewing, to make X and Y triangular like 2D.
161                // Orthonormal rotation. Not a skew transform.
162                double xy = x + y;
163                double s2 = xy * -0.211324865405187;
164                double zz = z * 0.577350269189626;
165                double xr = x + s2 - zz, yr = y + s2 - zz;
166                double zr = xy * 0.577350269189626 + zz;
167                
168                // Evaluate both lattices to form a BCC lattice.
169                return noise3_BCC(xr, yr, zr);
170        }

172        /**
173         * 3D Re-oriented 8-point BCC noise, with better visual isotropy in (X, Z).
174         * Recommended for 3D terrain and time-varied animations.
175         * The Y coordinate should always be the "different" coordinate in your use case.
176         * If Y is vertical in world coordinates, call noise3_XZBeforeY(x, Y, z).
177         * If Z is vertical in world coordinates, call noise3_XZBeforeY(x, Z, y) or use noise3_XYBeforeZ.
178         * For a time varied animation, call noise3_XZBeforeY(x, T, y) or use noise3_XYBeforeZ.
179         */
180        public double noise3_XZBeforeY(double x, double y, double z) {
181                
182                // Re-orient the cubic lattices without skewing, to make X and Z triangular like 2D.
183                // Orthonormal rotation. Not a skew transform.
184                double xz = x + z;
185                double s2 = xz * -0.211324865405187;
186                double yy = y * 0.577350269189626;
187                double xr = x + s2 - yy; double zr = z + s2 - yy;
188                double yr = xz * 0.577350269189626 + yy;
189                
190                // Evaluate both lattices to form a BCC lattice.
191                return noise3_BCC(xr, yr, zr);
192        }

194        /**
195         * Generate overlapping cubic lattices for 3D Re-oriented BCC noise.
196         * Lookup table implementation inspired by DigitalShadow.
197         * It was actually faster to narrow down the points in the loop itself,
198         * than to build up the index with enough info to isolate 8 points.
199         */
200        private double noise3_BCC(double xr, double yr, double zr) {
201                
202                // Get base and offsets inside cube of first lattice.
203                long xrb = Noise.longFloor(xr), yrb = Noise.longFloor(yr), zrb = Noise.longFloor(zr);
204                double xri = xr - xrb, yri = yr - yrb, zri = zr - zrb;
205                
206                // Identify which octant of the cube we're in. This determines which cell
207                // in the other cubic lattice we're in, and also narrows down one point on each.
208                int xht = (int)(xri + 0.5), yht = (int)(yri + 0.5), zht = (int)(zri + 0.5);
209                int index = (xht << 0) | (yht << 1) | (zht << 2);
210                
211                // Point contributions
212                double value = 0;
213                LatticePoint3D c = LOOKUP_3D[index];
214                while (c != null) {
215                        double dxr = xri + c.dxr, dyr = yri + c.dyr, dzr = zri + c.dzr;
216                        double attn = 0.75 - dxr * dxr - dyr * dyr - dzr * dzr;
217                        if (attn < 0) {
218                                c = c.nextOnFailure;
219                        } else {
220                                int pxm = ((int) xrb + c.xrv) & PMASK, pym = ((int) yrb + c.yrv) & PMASK, pzm = ((int) zrb + c.zrv) & PMASK;
221                                Grad3 grad = permGrad3[perm[perm[pxm] ^ pym] ^ pzm];
222                                double extrapolation = grad.dx * dxr + grad.dy * dyr + grad.dz * dzr;
223                                
224                                attn *= attn;
225                                value += attn * attn * extrapolation;
226                                c = c.nextOnSuccess;
227                        }
228                }
229                return value;
230        }

232        /**
233         * 4D SuperSimplex noise, classic lattice orientation.
234         */
235        public double noise4_Classic(double x, double y, double z, double w) {
236                
237                // Get points for A4 lattice
238                double s = 0.309016994374947 * (x + y + z + w);
239                double xs = x + s, ys = y + s, zs = z + s, ws = w + s;
240                
241                return noise4_Base(xs, ys, zs, ws);
242        }

244        /**
245         * 4D SuperSimplex noise, with XY and ZW forming orthogonal triangular-based planes.
246         * Recommended for 3D terrain, where X and Y (or Z and W) are horizontal.
247         * Recommended for noise(x, y, sin(time), cos(time)) trick.
248         */
249        public double noise4_XYBeforeZW(double x, double y, double z, double w) {
250                
251                double s2 = (x + y) * -0.28522513987434876941 + (z + w) * 0.83897065470611435718;
252                double t2 = (z + w) * 0.21939749883706435719 + (x + y) * -0.48214856493302476942;
253                double xs = x + s2, ys = y + s2, zs = z + t2, ws = w + t2;
254                
255                return noise4_Base(xs, ys, zs, ws);
256        }
257        
258        /**
259         * 4D SuperSimplex noise, with XZ and YW forming orthogonal triangular-based planes.
260         * Recommended for 3D terrain, where X and Z (or Y and W) are horizontal.
261         */
262        public double noise4_XZBeforeYW(double x, double y, double z, double w) {
263                
264                double s2 = (x + z) * -0.28522513987434876941 + (y + w) * 0.83897065470611435718;
265                double t2 = (y + w) * 0.21939749883706435719 + (x + z) * -0.48214856493302476942;
266                double xs = x + s2, ys = y + t2, zs = z + s2, ws = w + t2;
267                
268                return noise4_Base(xs, ys, zs, ws);
269        }

271        /**
272         * 4D SuperSimplex noise, with XYZ oriented like noise3_Classic,
273         * and W for an extra degree of freedom.
274         * Recommended for time-varied animations which texture a 3D object (W=time)
275         */
276        public double noise4_XYZBeforeW(double x, double y, double z, double w) {
277                
278                double xyz = x + y + z;
279                double ww = w * 1.118033988749894;
280                double s2 = xyz * -0.16666666666666666 + ww;
281                double xs = x + s2, ys = y + s2, zs = z + s2, ws = -0.5 * xyz + ww;
282                
283                return noise4_Base(xs, ys, zs, ws);
284        }

286        /**
287         * 4D SuperSimplex noise base.
288         * Using ultra-simple 4x4x4x4 lookup partitioning.
289         * This isn't as elegant or SIMD/GPU/etc. portable as other approaches,
290         * but it does compete performance-wise with optimized OpenSimplex1.
291         */
292        private double noise4_Base(double xs, double ys, double zs, double ws) {
293                double value = 0;
294                
295                // Get base points and offsets
296                long xsb = Noise.longFloor(xs), ysb = Noise.longFloor(ys), zsb = Noise.longFloor(zs), wsb = Noise.longFloor(ws);
297                double xsi = xs - xsb, ysi = ys - ysb, zsi = zs - zsb, wsi = ws - wsb;
298                
299                // Unskewed offsets
300                double ssi = (xsi + ysi + zsi + wsi) * -0.138196601125011;
301                double xi = xsi + ssi, yi = ysi + ssi, zi = zsi + ssi, wi = wsi + ssi;
302                        
303                int index = (int) ((Noise.longFloor(xs * 4) & 3L)
304                        | ((Noise.longFloor(ys * 4) & 3L) << 2)
305                        | ((Noise.longFloor(zs * 4) & 3L) << 4)
306                        | ((Noise.longFloor(ws * 4) & 3L) << 6));
307                
308                // Point contributions
309                for (LatticePoint4D c : LOOKUP_4D[index]) {
310                        double dx = xi + c.dx, dy = yi + c.dy, dz = zi + c.dz, dw = wi + c.dw;
311                        double attn = 0.8 - dx * dx - dy * dy - dz * dz - dw * dw;
312                        if (attn > 0) {
313                                attn *= attn;
314
315                                int pxm = ((int) xsb + c.xsv) & PMASK, pym = ((int) ysb + c.ysv) & PMASK;
316                                int pzm = ((int) zsb + c.zsv) & PMASK, pwm = ((int) wsb + c.wsv) & PMASK;
317                                Grad4 grad = permGrad4[perm[perm[perm[pxm] ^ pym] ^ pzm] ^ pwm];
318                                double extrapolation = grad.dx * dx + grad.dy * dy + grad.dz * dz + grad.dw * dw;
319                                
320                                value += attn * attn * extrapolation;
321                        }
322                }
323                return value;
324        }

330        private static int fastFloor(double x) {
331                int xi = (int)x;
332                return x < xi ? xi - 1 : xi;
333        }

339        private static final LatticePoint2D[] LOOKUP_2D;
340        private static final LatticePoint3D[] LOOKUP_3D;
341        private static final LatticePoint4D[][] LOOKUP_4D;
342        static {
343                LOOKUP_2D = new LatticePoint2D[8 * 4];
344                LOOKUP_3D = new LatticePoint3D[8];
345                LOOKUP_4D = new LatticePoint4D[256][];
346                
347                for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
348                        int i1, j1, i2, j2;
349                        if ((i & 1) == 0) {
350                                if ((i & 2) == 0) { i1 = -1; j1 = 0; } else { i1 = 1; j1 = 0; }
351                                if ((i & 4) == 0) { i2 = 0; j2 = -1; } else { i2 = 0; j2 = 1; }
352                        } else {
353                                if ((i & 2) != 0) { i1 = 2; j1 = 1; } else { i1 = 0; j1 = 1; }
354                                if ((i & 4) != 0) { i2 = 1; j2 = 2; } else { i2 = 1; j2 = 0; }
355                        }
356                        LOOKUP_2D[i * 4 + 0] = new LatticePoint2D(0, 0);
357                        LOOKUP_2D[i * 4 + 1] = new LatticePoint2D(1, 1);
358                        LOOKUP_2D[i * 4 + 2] = new LatticePoint2D(i1, j1);
359                        LOOKUP_2D[i * 4 + 3] = new LatticePoint2D(i2, j2);
360                }
361                
362                for (int i = 0; i < 8; i++) {
363                        int i1, j1, k1, i2, j2, k2;
364                        i1 = (i >> 0) & 1; j1 = (i >> 1) & 1; k1 = (i >> 2) & 1;
365                        i2 = i1 ^ 1; j2 = j1 ^ 1; k2 = k1 ^ 1;
366                        
367                        // The two points within this octant, one from each of the two cubic half-lattices.
368                        LatticePoint3D c0 = new LatticePoint3D(i1, j1, k1, 0);
369                        LatticePoint3D c1 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + i2, j1 + j2, k1 + k2, 1);
370                        
371                        // (1, 0, 0) vs (0, 1, 1) away from octant.
372                        LatticePoint3D c2 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 ^ 1, j1, k1, 0);
373                        LatticePoint3D c3 = new LatticePoint3D(i1, j1 ^ 1, k1 ^ 1, 0);
374                        
375                        // (1, 0, 0) vs (0, 1, 1) away from octant, on second half-lattice.
376                        LatticePoint3D c4 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + (i2 ^ 1), j1 + j2, k1 + k2, 1);
377                        LatticePoint3D c5 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + i2, j1 + (j2 ^ 1), k1 + (k2 ^ 1), 1);
378                        
379                        // (0, 1, 0) vs (1, 0, 1) away from octant.
380                        LatticePoint3D c6 = new LatticePoint3D(i1, j1 ^ 1, k1, 0);
381                        LatticePoint3D c7 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 ^ 1, j1, k1 ^ 1, 0);
382                        
383                        // (0, 1, 0) vs (1, 0, 1) away from octant, on second half-lattice.
384                        LatticePoint3D c8 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + i2, j1 + (j2 ^ 1), k1 + k2, 1);
385                        LatticePoint3D c9 = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + (i2 ^ 1), j1 + j2, k1 + (k2 ^ 1), 1);
386                        
387                        // (0, 0, 1) vs (1, 1, 0) away from octant.
388                        LatticePoint3D cA = new LatticePoint3D(i1, j1, k1 ^ 1, 0);
389                        LatticePoint3D cB = new LatticePoint3D(i1 ^ 1, j1 ^ 1, k1, 0);
390                        
391                        // (0, 0, 1) vs (1, 1, 0) away from octant, on second half-lattice.
392                        LatticePoint3D cC = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + i2, j1 + j2, k1 + (k2 ^ 1), 1);
393                        LatticePoint3D cD = new LatticePoint3D(i1 + (i2 ^ 1), j1 + (j2 ^ 1), k1 + k2, 1);
394                        
395                        // First two points are guaranteed.
396                        c0.nextOnFailure = c0.nextOnSuccess = c1;
397                        c1.nextOnFailure = c1.nextOnSuccess = c2;
398                        
399                        // If c2 is in range, then we know c3 and c4 are not.
400                        c2.nextOnFailure = c3; c2.nextOnSuccess = c5;
401                        c3.nextOnFailure = c4; c3.nextOnSuccess = c4;
402                        
403                        // If c4 is in range, then we know c5 is not.
404                        c4.nextOnFailure = c5; c4.nextOnSuccess = c6;
405                        c5.nextOnFailure = c5.nextOnSuccess = c6;
406                        
407                        // If c6 is in range, then we know c7 and c8 are not.
408                        c6.nextOnFailure = c7; c6.nextOnSuccess = c9;
409                        c7.nextOnFailure = c8; c7.nextOnSuccess = c8;
410                        
411                        // If c8 is in range, then we know c9 is not.
412                        c8.nextOnFailure = c9; c8.nextOnSuccess = cA;
413                        c9.nextOnFailure = c9.nextOnSuccess = cA;
414                        
415                        // If cA is in range, then we know cB and cC are not.
416                        cA.nextOnFailure = cB; cA.nextOnSuccess = cD;
417                        cB.nextOnFailure = cC; cB.nextOnSuccess = cC;
418                        
419                        // If cC is in range, then we know cD is not.
420                        cC.nextOnFailure = cD; cC.nextOnSuccess = null;
421                        cD.nextOnFailure = cD.nextOnSuccess = null;
422                        
423                        LOOKUP_3D[i] = c0;
424                }

730        private static class LatticePoint2D {
731                int xsv, ysv;
732                double dx, dy;
733                public LatticePoint2D(int xsv, int ysv) {
734                        this.xsv = xsv; this.ysv = ysv;
735                        double ssv = (xsv + ysv) * -0.211324865405187;
736                        this.dx = -xsv - ssv;
737                        this.dy = -ysv - ssv;
738                }

746                        this.dxr = -xrv + lattice * 0.5; this.dyr = -yrv + lattice * 0.5; this.dzr = -zrv + lattice * 0.5;

751        private static class LatticePoint4D {
752                int xsv, ysv, zsv, wsv;
753                double dx, dy, dz, dw;
754                public LatticePoint4D(int xsv, int ysv, int zsv, int wsv) {
755                        this.xsv = xsv; this.ysv = ysv; this.zsv = zsv; this.wsv = wsv;
756                        double ssv = (xsv + ysv + zsv + wsv) * -0.138196601125011;
757                        this.dx = -xsv - ssv;
758                        this.dy = -ysv - ssv;
759                        this.dz = -zsv - ssv;
760                        this.dw = -wsv - ssv;
761                }
